President Barack Obama has proclaimed November 2010 as National Alzheimer's Disease Awareness Month. In his proclamation, he highlights the devastating impact of Alzheimer's disease on individuals and their families. He emphasizes the need to improve detection, treatment, and find a cure for the disease. The American Recovery and Reinvestment Act is mentioned as a source of funding for research on risk factors, diagnostic tools, therapies, and preventive measures. The Affordable Care Act is also highlighted for its contributions to Alzheimer's care, including the establishment of the Cures Acceleration Network, training for nursing home workers, and the Community Living Assistance Services and Supports (CLASS) Program. The legislation also provides free annual wellness visits for Medicare beneficiaries to detect cognitive impairment early. President Obama calls for support for Alzheimer's research and caregivers, acknowledging their crucial role in caring for individuals with the disease.